# cMesh Coding Rules for Claude Code

## Architecture & Data Flow

### Core Modules
- `Common/` hosts math helpers (`BoundingBox{2,3}D`, `MathConverter`, `Types`) that every module includes; keep new utilities dependency-free so they can compile in headers.
- `Utils/` provides cross-cutting utilities like `MeshLogger` for debugging and logging mesh data.

### Geometry (2D & 3D)
- **3D Geometry**: Lives behind interfaces in `src/Geometry/Base` (`ISurface3D`, `IEdge3D`, `ICorner3D`, `GeometryCollection3D`) while `Geometry/OpenCascade` supplies concrete OpenCascade-backed shapes; treat `GeometryCollection3D` as the single entry point for 3D geometry data.
- **2D Geometry**: `Geometry2D/` provides 2D geometry abstractions (`Corner2D`, `LinearEdge2D`, `IEdge2D`, `GeometryCollection2D`); use `GeometryOperations2D` for extracting points and discretizing edges with `DiscretizationSettings2D`.
- **Usage**: In the code, use ONLY THE INTERFACES! We do not want to be dependent on OpenCascade or any other external software. These must be kept optional.

### Topology (2D & 3D)
- **3D Topology**: `Topology/Topology3D` mirrors geometry IDs and provides validation helpers (`isValid`, `isManifold`) that meshing code calls before generating elements.
- **2D Topology**: `Topology2D/` provides `Corner2D`, `Edge2D`, and `Topology2D` for 2D topological data.

### Meshing
- **Data Structures**: `Meshing/Data/` contains separate data structures for 2D (`MeshData2D`, `Node2D`, `TriangleElement`) and 3D (`MeshData3D`, `Node3D`, `TetrahedralElement`) plus shared `MeshConnectivity`.
- **Contexts**: `MeshingContext2D` and `MeshingContext3D` tie geometry + topology to mutable mesh state; call `getMeshData()/getConnectivity()` through the context instead of caching pointers.
- **Algorithms**: Located in `Meshing/Core/2D/` and `Meshing/Core/3D/`
  - **2D**: `ConstrainedDelaunay2D` (dual-mode: context-based or standalone), `Delaunay2D`, `Computer2D` (geometric computations), `MeshOperations2D` (high-level operations), `MeshVerifier` (validation)
  - **3D**: `MeshOperations3D`, `ShewchukRefiner3D`, `ElementGeometry3D`, `ElementQuality3D`, `ConstraintChecker3D`, `GeometryUtilities3D`, `QualityComputer`
- **Mutators**: `MeshMutator2D` and `MeshMutator3D` provide low-level mutation operations; use `MeshOperations` helpers for higher-level transactions.
- **Interfaces**: `Meshing/Interfaces/` contains `IMesher` and `IQualityController`.
- See `Meshing/Core/DIRECTORY_OVERVIEW.md` for comprehensive organization details.

### Export
- `Export/VtkExporter` currently emits ASCII `.vtu` files (supports triangles and tetrahedra); integration tests (`tests/Integration/test_VtkExporter.cpp`) assert the full XML skeleton, so keep new tags consistent.
- New exporters should implement `IExporter` interface.

## Key Modules & Extension Points

### Readers & CAD Import
- `Readers/OpenCascade` + `TopoDS_ShapeConverter` create `GeometryCollection3D`/`Topology3D` pairs from CAD files.
- Add new importers by returning the same geometry/topology abstractions to keep solvers engine-agnostic.

### Meshing Data & Operations
- **Data Structures**: `MeshData2D`, `MeshData3D`, and `MeshConnectivity` own `std::unique_ptr` containers and expose mutation only through friend APIs; never modify containers directly.
- **Mutators**: `MeshMutator2D` and `MeshMutator3D` provide low-level mutation operations with friend access to data structures.
- **High-Level Operations**: `MeshOperations2D` provides algorithms like cavity finding, edge enforcement, and point location for 2D meshes.
- **Transactions**: Transaction-style helpers in `Meshing/Operations/` update nodes/elements and rebuild adjacency; call `MeshingContext::rebuildConnectivity()` after bulk edits.

### Export & Visualization
- `Export/IExporter` is intentionally minimal—new exporters should mimic `VtkExporter::exportMesh` signature and keep file I/O streaming (std::ostream) friendly.
- Current support: VTK/VTU format for triangles and tetrahedra.

### Examples & Testing
- `src/Examples/*.cc` includes: `BoxWithHole.cc`, `ConstrainedBoxExample.cc`, `CreateBox.cc`, `RectangleWithCrack.cc`, `RectangleWithHole2D.cc`, `SimpleDelaunay2D.cc`.
- Examples link every core library plus OpenCascade/VTK (see `src/Examples/CMakeLists.txt`) and are the fastest way to exercise end-to-end workflows outside tests.
- Tests organized by module in `tests/` with GoogleTest framework; integration tests in `tests/Integration/`.

## Build & Test Workflow

### CMake Configuration
- Configure with `cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug` (pins Clang, enables `-g3 -O0`); rerun when dependencies change.
- CMake requires version 3.16+ and uses C++17 standard.
- Dependencies: VTK, Eigen3, spdlog, fmt, GoogleTest, OpenCascade.
- Ensure `OpenCASCADE_DIR` resolves to `$HOME/lib/opencascade/lib/cmake/opencascade` or override before configuring.

### Building
- Build everything: `cmake --build build -j$(nproc)`
- Binaries land in `build/src/Examples/` and `build/tests/runTests`.

### Testing
- Run full GoogleTest suite: `ctest --test-dir build/tests --output-on-failure`
- Or launch directly: `./build/tests/runTests`
- Tests cover: geometry primitives (2D & 3D), topology, meshing data/core/operations, and integration workflows.
- Integration tests validate full pipelines including VTK export.

## Coding Standards (Must Follow)

### File Organization
- Headers: `.h` extension, sources: `.cpp` extension
- One class per file, use `#pragma once` for header guards
- Only declarations in headers, implementations in `.cpp` files
- Structs should be in separate header files organized by library
- No `using namespace` directives in any file

### Naming Conventions
- Classes: `CamelCase` (e.g., `ConstrainedDelaunay2D`, `MeshData3D`)
- Interfaces: Must start with capital `I` (e.g., `ICorner3D`, `IEdge3D`, `ISurface3D`)
  - File containing the interface must also start with `I` (e.g., `ICorner3D.h`, not `Corner3D.h`)
- Variables: `camelCase` (e.g., `nodeCount`, `triangleIndex`)
- Member variables: `camelCase_` with trailing underscore (e.g., `nodes_`, `connectivity_`)
- Constants: `ALL_CAPS` (e.g., `MAX_ITERATIONS`)
- Getters: `get...()` (e.g., `getNodes()`, `getEdgeCount()`)
- Setters: `set...()` (e.g., `setTolerance()`, `setMaxIterations()`)

### Functions & Methods
- Prefer `const` correctness everywhere (const methods, const references)
- Pass non-primitives by `const&` (e.g., `const Point3D&`, `const std::vector<Node>&`)
- One declaration per line (no `int a, b, c;`)
- Use `auto` when it improves clarity, but prefer explicit types for interfaces

### Classes & Access Control
- No public or protected data members (use getters/setters)
  - Exception: `struct` types used as plain data containers (e.g., `Circle2D`, `PointExtractionResult`) may have public members
  - Rationale: Structs are semantically data containers; forcing getters/setters adds boilerplate without encapsulation benefit
- **Friend classes**: General rule is NO friend classes
  - Exception: `MeshData2D` ↔ `MeshMutator2D` and `MeshData3D` ↔ `MeshMutator3D` for controlled mutation access
  - Rationale: Enforces encapsulation while avoiding public setters for internal containers
  - New friend relationships require strong architectural justification and approval
- Ownership via `std::unique_ptr` for heap-allocated objects
- Only use `static_cast` and `dynamic_cast` (no C-style casts)
- Prefer composition over inheritance

### Constructors & Initialization
- Use `explicit` on all single-argument constructors (prevents implicit conversions)
- Member initializer lists: one member per line for readability
- Default constructors: use `= default` when compiler-generated version is appropriate
- Destructors: use `= default` for simple classes, `virtual ~ClassName() = default` for base classes
- **Copy/Move semantics**:
  - Classes with `std::unique_ptr` members automatically have copy operations deleted by the compiler (move operations are auto-generated)
  - Explicitly deleting copy operations is optional but can improve code documentation
  - If copy is desired for a class with unique_ptr, implement custom copy constructor/assignment that performs deep copy
- Default parameters: allowed, no limits on usage

### Headers & Includes
- Include paths relative to `src/` (e.g., `#include "Meshing/Data/MeshData2D.h"`)
- Favor forward declarations in headers to minimize dependencies
- Include concrete headers in `.cpp` files only
- See `Meshing/Interfaces/IMesher.h` for forward declaration examples
- **Include order**: Own header first (for .cpp files), then all other includes alphabetically
- Keep files small with one class - include sections should be short

### Namespaces
- Wrap code in namespaces: `namespace cMesh { ... }`
- No nested namespace declarations in C++17 (use separate lines if needed)
- **Using declarations**:
  - Allowed in `.cpp` files for convenience (e.g., `using std::vector;`, `using Meshing::Point2D;`)
  - NOT allowed in `.h` header files - use fully qualified names instead
  - Never use `using namespace` directives anywhere

### Comments & Documentation
- Keep comments minimal - code should be self-documenting through descriptive naming
- Use comments only when naming alone cannot convey the intent or complexity
- If code requires extensive comments to understand, consider refactoring into smaller, clearer chunks
- Inline comments: use `//` sparingly for non-obvious logic or algorithmic decisions
- No mandatory Doxygen comments - reserve for truly complex APIs if needed
- Exception: brief comments acceptable for algorithmic rationale or mathematical concepts

### Error Handling & Exceptions
**IMPORTANT: See `doc/Error_Handling.md` for complete error handling guide.**

Quick reference:
- **Exceptions** (typed): Use custom exceptions from `Common/Exceptions/` for errors
  - Entity lookups that should succeed: `CMESH_THROW_ENTITY_NOT_FOUND("Type", id)`
  - Null pointer validation: `CMESH_REQUIRE_NOT_NULL(ptr, "name")`
  - Operations that fail: `CMESH_THROW_CODE(ExceptionType, ErrorCode::CODE, "message")`
  - Mesh verification: `CMESH_THROW_VERIFICATION_FAILED("msg", errorList)`
- **std::optional<T>**: Use for operations that may legitimately produce no result
  - Geometric computations on degenerate elements (circumcircle, quality metrics)
  - Query operations where "not found" is valid (findVertexId, findSurfaceAt)
- **bool**: Use for simple success/failure or yes/no queries
  - Try operations: `bool tryEnforceConstraint(...)`
  - Query operations: `bool contains(...)`
- **Structured results**: Use for validation needing error lists (`VerificationResult`)
- **File I/O**: Enable stream exceptions (`os.exceptions(std::ios::failbit | std::ios::badbit)`)
- **Never use**: Generic `std::runtime_error`, assertions for validation

## Implementation Tips & Best Practices

### Code Organization
- Favor forward declarations in headers and include concrete headers in `.cpp` files to minimize compile dependencies
- See `Meshing/Interfaces/IMesher.h` for examples of proper forward declaration usage
- Consult `doc/Meshing_Core_Overview.md` for meshing module organization and patterns

### Testing
- **Test naming**: Use `TEST(ClassName, DescriptiveBehavior)` format
  - ClassName: The class being tested
  - DescriptiveBehavior: What the test verifies (e.g., `TriangulatesSimpleSquare`, `HandlesEmptyInput`)
- **Assertions**: Prefer `EXPECT_*` for non-fatal checks, `ASSERT_*` only when test cannot continue
  - Use `EXPECT_EQ`, `EXPECT_TRUE`, `EXPECT_FALSE`, etc.
- **File organization**: One test file per class, matching filename: `test_ClassName.cpp`
- **Test structure**: Organize by module in `tests/` subdirectories
  - Unit tests: `tests/ModuleName/` (e.g., `tests/Meshing/Core/`)
  - Integration tests: `tests/Integration/` for full workflows
- **CMake**: When adding new tests, update `tests/CMakeLists.txt` to link against appropriate libraries (`Geometry`, `Geometry2D`, `Topology`, `Topology2D`, `Meshing`, `Export`, `Readers`, `Common`, `Utils`)
- **Namespaces in tests**: `using namespace` is acceptable in test .cpp files and example .cc files for convenience

### 2D vs 3D Patterns
- Maintain clear separation between 2D and 3D code (separate classes, separate directories)
- 2D code goes in `Meshing/Core/2D/`, 3D code in `Meshing/Core/3D/`
- Shared utilities can live in `Meshing/Core/` or appropriate parent directory
- Use `GeometryOperations2D` for 2D geometry utilities, similar patterns for 3D

### Data Access Patterns
- Access mesh data through contexts (`MeshingContext2D`, `MeshingContext3D`) using `getMeshData()` and `getConnectivity()`
- Never cache raw pointers to mesh data; always go through the context
- Use `MeshMutator2D/3D` for low-level mutations, `MeshOperations2D` for higher-level algorithms
- Rebuild connectivity after bulk operations: `context.rebuildConnectivity()`

### Documentation & Background
- Check `doc/Other/MeshData_C++20_Improvements.md` for background on data structure design choices
- Consult existing documentation in `doc/` and `docs/` before major refactoring

### Utilities
- Use `MeshLogger` from `Utils/` for debugging mesh data
- Use `MeshVerifier` (2D) for validating mesh orientation and detecting overlaps
- Use `Computer2D` and `Computer3D` for geometric calculations (circumcircles, orientations, etc.)
